# HDIM Project Rules

## Web Content Creation Process

### Overview
When creating web-ready HTML versions of markdown documentation, follow this standardized process to ensure consistency and maintainability.

### Location
- **Markdown Source:** `docs/marketing/*.md`
- **HTML Output:** `docs/marketing/web/*.html`
- **Conversion Script:** `docs/marketing/web/convert-to-html.py`
- **Index Page:** `docs/marketing/web/ai-solutioning-index.html`

### Process Steps

#### 1. Create/Update Markdown Documentation
- Write or update markdown files in `docs/marketing/`
- Follow standard markdown formatting
- Include frontmatter if needed (will be stripped during conversion)

#### 2. Update Document Metadata
If adding new documents, update `convert-to-html.py`:
```python
DOCUMENTS = {
    'filename.md': {
        'title': 'Document Title',
        'subtitle': 'Document Subtitle',
        'icon': '📖'  # Emoji icon
    },
    # ... existing documents
}
```

#### 3. Generate HTML Files
Run the conversion script:
```bash
cd docs/marketing/web
python3 convert-to-html.py
```

The script will:
- Read markdown files from parent directory (`../`)
- Convert markdown to HTML with basic formatting
- Apply consistent template with navigation and styling
- Write HTML files to `docs/marketing/web/`

#### 4. Update Index Page (if needed)
If adding new documents, update `ai-solutioning-index.html`:
- Add new document card in the documents grid
- Update navigation if needed
- Ensure links point to correct HTML files

#### 5. Test Locally
- Open `ai-solutioning-index.html` in a web browser
- Verify all links work
- Check responsive design (desktop, tablet, mobile)
- Validate HTML structure

#### 6. Commit and Push
```bash
git add docs/marketing/web/
git commit -m "feat: update web content for [document name]"
git push origin master
```

### HTML Template Features

The template includes:
- **Responsive Design:** Works on desktop, tablet, mobile
- **Consistent Navigation:** Fixed nav bar with links
- **Hero Sections:** Gradient backgrounds with titles
- **Content Styling:** Typography, spacing, colors
- **Print-Friendly:** Can be saved as PDF
- **SEO-Friendly:** Meta tags included

### Design System

**Colors:**
- Primary: `#1E3A5F` (Dark Blue)
- Secondary: `#00A9A5` (Teal)
- Accent: `#2E7D32` (Green)
- Text: `#2C3E50` (Dark Gray)
- Light: `#F5F7FA` (Light Gray)

**Typography:**
- Font: Inter (Google Fonts)
- Headings: 700-800 weight
- Body: 400 weight, 1.8 line height

**Layout:**
- Max width: 900px (content), 1200px (index)
- Responsive breakpoint: 768px
- Fixed navigation bar
- Hero sections with gradients

### Markdown to HTML Conversion

The conversion script handles:
- Headers (H1-H4)
- Bold and italic text
- Code blocks and inline code
- Links
- Horizontal rules
- Basic lists
- Paragraphs

**Limitations:**
- Complex markdown features may need manual adjustment
- Tables require proper markdown formatting
- Nested lists may need review
- Code block syntax highlighting not included

### Deployment Options

HTML files can be deployed to:
- **Vercel:** Static site hosting
- **GitHub Pages:** Free hosting
- **Netlify:** Static site hosting
- **Any web server:** Standard HTML files

### Maintenance

**When to Regenerate:**
- After updating markdown source files
- When adding new documents
- When changing template design
- Before deployment

**Best Practices:**
- Keep markdown as source of truth
- Regenerate HTML after markdown changes
- Test locally before committing
- Document any manual HTML adjustments needed

### File Structure

```
docs/marketing/
├── *.md                          # Markdown source files
└── web/
    ├── README.md                 # Usage instructions
    ├── convert-to-html.py        # Conversion script
    ├── ai-solutioning-index.html # Main index page
    └── *.html                    # Generated HTML pages
```

### Notes

- The markdown to HTML conversion is basic - complex markdown features may need manual adjustment
- Tables, code blocks, and lists are supported
- Links to external resources work as-is
- Internal links between documents work via relative paths
- All styling is in `<style>` tags within each HTML file for portability
